CsidqdHwQkgFzHuzQ4QN7N1Mj_QuB6zAlRxqiwpJ77TM_YkrzDGi0J7fLACchgBzkIxnJ0BHSpdDaUMzWQ==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering classpath and testing**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the compileTestJava classpath. It seems that it should include destinationDir after the compilation step, not source dir, which leads to issues with compiling tests that reference it. I wonder if changing the test's `resolveWithCompilerGeneratedClassResolver` to use reflection with Class.forName could work? Maybe using MethodHandles to instantiate a generated binary helper without an import could solve the problem. If I can direct invoke with coverage, I need to ensure the .class file gets created.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring testing functions**\\n\\nIt looks like the tck only runs nativeTest. For a dynamic report, I might need to use a native run instead. If I'm using native, it seems that the closure init can fail, leading to tests catching LinkageError because no class$ is invoked. But wait, is the coverage coming from the JVM? I want to confirm if I can access the dynamic report after the last one. It’s important to ensure that class$ can be invoked without requiring the initialization of the closure class.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Verifying class coverage**\\n\\nI’m thinking about coverage showing false. I wonder if it’s because the caller class is considered test code, not part of the library due to the instrumented closure class coming from build/classes. I need to verify if the class in the closure from the original jar is instrumented or coming from cache. Also, the tests’ runtime classpath might be using a dependency jar that isn’t effectively instrumented. Could dynamic coverage at runtime fail to instrument synthetic classes? Hmm, that’s interesting to explore.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering code optimization**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how the native code sees a static reference and includes a